    Anos & Penes & Pussys\\
    \hline
    A & B & C\\
    \hdashline[4pt/4pt]
    \multirow{3}{*}{D} & E & F\\
    & G & H\\
    & I & J\\
    \hdashline
    \multirow{2}{*}{K}& L & M\\
    & N & O\\
    \hline
  \end{tabular}
\end{center}
\end{minipage}
\subsection{Colors}
\paragraph{}
The package \texttt{colortbl} enable us different comands to change row color, column color or cell color. The package \texttt{xcolor} let's you use all of the premade colors and create more. *color-name!30 you'll use 30\% of that color*.
\subsubsection{Row}
\paragraph{}
In order to change the entire row color use the \textbackslash rowcolor \{color!color\%\} command before the row begins.
\paragraph{}

\begin{minipage}{.45\textwidth}
\begin{lstlisting}[basicstyle=\footnotesize,]{Name}
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}
  \hline
  Anos & Penes & Pussys\\
  \hline
  \rowcolor{green!30}
  A & B & C\\
  \hline
  \rowcolor{blue!30}
  D & E & F \\
  \hline
  \rowcolor{red!15}
  G & H & I \\
  \hline
\end{tabular}
\end{lstlisting}
\end{minipage}\hfill
\begin{minipage}{.45\textwidth}
  \begin{center}
  \renewcommand{\arraystretch}{2}
  \begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}
    \hline
    Anos & Penes & Pussys\\
    \hline
    \rowcolor{green!30}
    A & B & C\\
    \hline
    \rowcolor{blue!30}
    D & E & F \\
    \hline
    \rowcolor{red!15}
    G & H & I \\
    \hline
  \end{tabular}
\end{center}
\end{minipage}
\subsubsection{Column}
\paragraph{}
This command colors an entire column $>$\{\textbackslash columncolor \{color!color\%\}\}. Needs to be written while defining columns.
\paragraph{}
\begin{minipage}{.45\textwidth}
\begin{lstlisting}[basicstyle=\footnotesize,]{Name}
\begin{tabular}{|
>{\columncolor{green!30}}c|
>{\columncolor{blue!30}}c|
>{\columncolor{red!15}}c|}
\hline
Anos & Penes & Pussys\\
\hline
A & B & C\\
\hdashline[4pt/4pt]
D & E & F \\
\hdashline[4pt/4pt]
G & H & I \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{lstlisting}
\end{minipage}\hfill
\begin{minipage}{.45\textwidth}
\begin{center}
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{2}
\begin{tabular}{|
  >{\columncolor{green!30}}c|
  >{\columncolor{blue!30}}c|
  >{\columncolor{red!15}}c|}
  \hline
  Anos & Penes & Pussys\\
  \hline
  A & B & C\\
  \hdashline[4pt/4pt]
  D & E & F \\
  \hdashline[4pt/4pt]
  G & H & I \\
  \hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
\end{minipage}

\subsubsection{Cell}
\paragraph{}
The syntax is quite similar to the rest \textbackslash cellcolor \{color!colo\%\}.
\paragraph{}
\begin{minipage}{.45\textwidth}
\begin{lstlisting}[basicstyle=\footnotesize,]{Name}
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}
\hline
Anos & Penes & Pussys\\
\hline
\cellcolor{green!30}A & B & C\\
\hdashline[4pt/4pt]
D & \cellcolor{blue!30} E & F \\
\hdashline[4pt/4pt]
G & H & \cellcolor{red!15}I \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{lstlisting}
\end{minipage}\hfill
\begin{minipage}{.45\textwidth}
\begin{center}
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{2}
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}
  \hline
  Anos & Penes & Pussys\\
  \hline
  \cellcolor{green!30}A & B & C\\
  \hdashline[4pt/4pt]
  D & \cellcolor{blue!30} E & F \\
  \hdashline[4pt/4pt]
  G & H & \cellcolor{red!15}I \\
  \hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
\end{minipage}

\subsubsection{Alternate rows}
\paragraph{}
First youll need to import the package xcolor as follows \textbackslash usepackage[table]\{xcolor\}. The command lets use colors to alternate rows of a table \textbackslash rowcolors \{starting row number\} \{odd row color\} \{even row color\}.This command is used before the tabular enclousure. *Color are defined as the last examples* *incompatible with dashed lines*
\paragraph{}

\begin{minipage}{.45\textwidth}
\begin{lstlisting}[basicstyle=\footnotesize,]{Name}
\rowcolors{1}{green!30}{red!15}
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}
\hline
Anos & Penes & Pussys\\
\hline
A & B & C\\
\hline
D & E & F \\
\hline
G & H & I \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{lstlisting}
\end{minipage}\hfill
\begin{minipage}{.45\textwidth}
\begin{center}
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{2}
\rowcolors{1}{green!30}{red!15}
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}
  \hline
  Anos & Penes & Pussys\\
  \hline
  A & B & C\\
  \hline
  D & E & F \\
  \hline
  G & H & I \\
  \hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
\end{minipage}

\subsection{Table enviroment}
\paragraph{}
The table enviroment is used to position the document and to specify the caption of the table.
\paragraph{}
\begin{lstlisting}[frame=single]
\begin{table}[POSITION-PARAMETER]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{...}
    .
    .
    .
\end{tabular}
\caption{text}
\end{table}
\end{lstlisting}
\paragraph{}
Useful commands
\begin{description}
\item[\textbackslash centering] centers the table on the page
\item[\textbackslash caption\{text\}] write a caption under the table
\item[\textbackslash listoftables] display the caption of all of the tables, usually written after the table of contents
\end{description}
\begin{table}[h]
\centering
  \renewcommand{\arraystretch}{2}
  \begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}
    \hline
    Anos & Penes & Pussys\\
    \hline
    A & B & C\\
    \hdashline[4pt/4pt]
    D & E & F \\
    \hdashline[4pt/4pt]
    G & H & I \\
    \hline
  \end{tabular}
  \caption{This a caption}
\end{table}
