\section{Images}
\paragraph{}
To include images we will use the package \texttt{graphicx}. The following file extentions are supported: .png , .jpg , .pdf and .eps. The command \texttt{includegraphics} is used to display images.
\paragraph{}
\begin{lstlisting}
  \usepackage{graphicx}
  \includegraphics[Atribute-1, Atribute-2, ...]{FileName.extention}
\end{lstlisting}
\subsection{Atributes}
\paragraph{}
There exists two atributes to size the image: width and height both can be specified in cm, inches, px, ...
\paragraph{}
Just specify one of them, the other parameter will change to maintain the same ratio.
\begin{itemize}
  \item width=X unit
  \item height=X unit
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[height=6cm]{C:/Users/miche/Desktop/LaTex_learning/selfmade man.png}
\end{center}
\paragraph{}
There exist the attribute scale that allows you to resize an image withou explicitly givin height or width.
\begin{itemize}
  \item scale=X
\end{itemize}
\paragraph{}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[scale=0.4]{C:/Users/miche/Desktop/LaTex_learning/selfmade man.png}
\end{center}
\paragraph{}
An image can also be trimed for that you will have to set the atribute clip to true and with the atribute trim you'll be able to specify how much and in wich units to trim each side.
\begin{itemize}
  \item clip=true, trim= Left cm  Bottom cm Right cm Top cm
\end{itemize}
\paragraph{}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[clip=true, trim= 3cm 6cm 3cm 4cm]{C:/Users/miche/Desktop/LaTex_learning/selfmade man.png}
\end{center}
\paragraph{}
The atribute angle lets you rotate images.
\begin{itemize}
  \item angle= $\alpha$ in degrees
\end{itemize}
\paragraph{}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[scale=.4, angle=45]{C:/Users/miche/Desktop/LaTex_learning/selfmade man.png}
\end{center}
\subsection{Image borders}
To create a border around your image use the command \textbackslash fbox.
\paragraph{}

\begin{lstlisting}
  \fbox{\includegraphics[Atribute-1, Atribute-2, ...]
    {FileName.extention}}
\end{lstlisting}
\paragraph{}
\begin{center}
\fbox{\includegraphics[scale=.4]{C:/Users/miche/Desktop/LaTex_learning/selfmade man.png}}
\end{center}
\paragraph{}
To adjust \textbf{image border} use the following command before the fbox.
\paragraph{}
  \begin{lstlisting}
    \setlength\fboxrule(thickness in pt)
    \fbox{\includegraphics[Atribute-1, Atribute-2, ...]
      {FileName.extention}}
  \end{lstlisting}

\paragraph{}
\begin{center}
\setlength\fboxrule{3pt}
\fbox{\includegraphics[scale=.4]{C:/Users/miche/Desktop/LaTex_learning/selfmade man.png}}
\end{center}
\paragraph{}
To set \textbf{ space between border and image} is a similar sintax than before
\paragraph{}
  \begin{lstlisting}
    \setlength\fboxsep(separation in pt)
    \fbox{\includegraphics[Atribute-1, Atribute-2, ...]
      {FileName.extention}}
  \end{lstlisting}

\paragraph{}
\begin{center}
\setlength\fboxsep{30pt}
\fbox{\includegraphics[scale=.4]{C:/Users/miche/Desktop/LaTex_learning/selfmade man.png}}
\end{center}
\paragraph{}

\subsection{Figure enviroment}
\paragraph{}
The figure enviroment is used to specify a certain position and ad captions.
\paragraph{}
\begin{lstlisting}
\begin{figure}[position]
  \includegraphics[Atribute-1, Atribute-2, ...]
    {FileName.extention}
  \caption{text}
\end{figure}
\end{lstlisting}
\begin{center}
  \begin{tabular}{|c|c|}
    \hline
    positions & \\
    \hline
    h & approximately here\\
    H & exactly here, as in . Tex file\\
    t & at the top of the page\\
    b & at the bottom of the page\\
    p & on a special page\\
    ! & overeide internal parameters\\
    \hline
  \end{tabular}
\end{center}
\paragraph{}
\begin{figure}[h!]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[scale=.4]{C:/Users/miche/Desktop/LaTex_learning/selfmade man.png}
  \caption{Self Made Man by Bobbie Carlyle }
\end{figure}
\paragraph{}
The command \textbackslash listoffigures display the caption of all the images, typically used after the table of contents

\subsection{Wrap figures}
\paragraph{}
There are 2 options to displace an image alongside text
\subsubsection{wrapfigure enviroment}
\paragraph{}
We'll use the package \texttt{wrapfig}.
\paragraph{}
\begin{lstlisting}
\begin{wrapfigure}{position}{number\textwidth}
  \includegraphics[Atribute-1, Atribute-2, ...]
    {FileName.extention}
  \caption{text}
\end{wrapfigure}
\end{lstlisting}
\begin{center}
  \begin{tabular}{|c|c|}
    \hline
    position &\\
    \hline
    l & image on the left and text on the right\\
    r & image on the right and text on the left\\
    i & inside edge\\
    o & away from binding (double pages)\\
    \hline
    Lower case & image placed exactly here\\
    Upper case & image can float\\
    \hline
  \end{tabular}
\end{center}
\begin{wrapfigure}{o}{0.4\textwidth}
\includegraphics[scale=.35]{C:/Users/miche/Desktop/LaTex_learning/selfmade man.png}
\caption{Self Made Man by Bobbie Carlyle}
\end{wrapfigure}
\paragraph{}
\textsf{\blindtext}
\subsubsection{figwindow enviroment}
\paragraph{}
To use this enviroment we will have to use the package \texttt{picinpar}.*Do not put a space between commas*
\paragraph{}
\begin{lstlisting}
\begin{figwindow}[lines-skipped,
    image-alignment(l,r,c),
    \includegraphics[Atribute-1, Atribute-2, ...]
    {FileName.extention},
    {caption}]
  text
\end{figwindow}
\end{lstlisting}
\paragraph{}

\begin{figwindow}[4,c,%
{\includegraphics[scale=.2]{C:/Users/miche/Desktop/LaTex_learning/selfmade man.png}},%
{Made Man by Bobbie Carlyle}]
\textsf{\Blindtext[2]}
\end{figwindow}
\section{Include Pdfs}
\paragraph{}
The package \texttt{pdfpages} let's you include pages from another .pdf document.
\paragraph{}
\begin{lstlisting}
  \usepackage[option]{pdfpages}
\end{lstlisting}
\paragraph{}
The available options are:
\begin{description}
  \item[final] inserts the .pdf file (default)
  \item[draft] inserts a blank box with the filename instead of the .pdf
  \item [demo] inserts an empty blank page instead of the .pdf file
\end{description}
\subsection{Insert pages}
The basic sintax is as follows:
\paragraph{}
\begin{lstlisting}
  \includepdf[pages={pages options}]{filename.pdf}
\end{lstlisting}
\paragraph{}
Every page option should be separated by commas ``,''
\paragraph{}
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{l|l}
  \hline
  Option & \\
  \hline
  nº & insert that page number\\
  \{\} & insert a blank page\\
  \{nº-nº\} & insert pages from the first to the last number\\
  pages=- & display the whole document\\
  \hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
\subsubsection{Page style}
\paragraph{}
using the pagecommand you can set a certain style (header and footer), note that the style options are the same of the whole document because we are using the command \textbackslash thispagestyle. \textcolor{red}{refer to pagestyle options}
\paragraph{}
You can also set it to fancy and use options of the \texttt{fancyhdr} package.\\

\begin{lstlisting}
  \includepdf[pages=-, pagecommand={\thispagestyle{option}}]
             {filename.pdf}
\end{lstlisting}
\subsubsection{Scale}
The size of the pages can be scaled in a similar way images do.\\
\begin{lstlisting}
  \includepdf[pages=-, scale=number]{filename.pdf}
\end{lstlisting}
\subsubsection{Crop}
A page can also be trimed for that set the atribute clip to true and with the atribute trim  specify how much and in wich units to trim each side.\\
\begin{lstlisting}
  \includepdf[pages=-, clip=true,
              trim= L mm Bottom mm Right mm Top mm]
             {filename.pdf}
\end{lstlisting}
\subsubsection{Rotate}
To rotate pages is the same way images are rotated \\
\begin{lstlisting}
  \includepdf[pages=-, angle= angle in degrees]
             {filename.pdf}
\end{lstlisting}
\section{Useful Packages}

\paragraph{blindtext}
Adds dummy text in your document to see how it looks. Use this code: \textbackslash blindtext

\paragraph{geometry}
This package,used in the docuement and package section, enables us to manage margins.\\
\textbackslash usepackage[margin=1in]\{geometry\} makes every margin of 1 inch\\
\textbackslash usepackage[top=1in, bottom=0.75in, left=1.25in, right=1.1in ]\{geometry\} handle each margin individually.\\
\textbackslash usepackage[inner=2in, outer=1in, top=3in, bottom=1in]\{geometry\} manage margins in two-sided documents

\paragraph{fancyhdr}
This package,used in the document info section, lets us be more precise in what we want to put in the header or footer. After \textbackslash usepackage\{fancyhdr\} we use \textbackslash pagestyle\{fancy\}. Now we can use
deifferent commands:\\
\textbackslash lhead\{...\}, \textbackslash rhead\{...\}, \textbackslash chead\{...\}\\ \textbackslash lfoot\{...\}, \textbackslash rfoot\{...\}, \textbackslash cfoot\{...\}\\
Between the brackets you can put text or comands to be shown in that especific place. Useful commands are:\\
\textbackslash thepage : shows the current page\\
\textbackslash chaptername : title ``chapter''\\
\textbackslash thechapter : chapter number\\
\textbackslash thesection : section number\\
\textbackslash pageref\{LastPage\} : total number of pages *lastpage package is needed*\\
To get rid of the header vanilla text use: \textbackslash fancyhead\{\}\\
To get rid of the header horizontal line: \textbackslash renewcommand \{\textbackslash headrulewidth\}\{0pt\}

\end{document}
